Step 1: Detect Humans¶

In this section, we use OpenCV's implementation of Haar feature-based cascade classifiers to detect human faces in images.

OpenCV provides many pre-trained face detectors, stored as XML files on github. We have downloaded one of these detectors and stored it in the haarcascades directory. In the next code cell, we demonstrate how to use this detector to find human faces in a sample image.

In [2]:
import cv2                
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt                        
%matplotlib inline                               


def show_face(img_path, scale=None):
    # extract pre-trained face detector
    face_cascade = cv2.CascadeClassifier('haarcascades/haarcascade_frontalface_alt.xml')

    # load color (BGR) image
    img = cv2.imread(img_path)
    
    # resize
    if scale:
        width = int(img.shape[1] * scale)
        height = int(img.shape[0] * scale)
        img = cv2.resize(img, (width, height), interpolation = cv2.INTER_AREA)

    # convert BGR image to grayscale
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

    # find faces in image
    faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray)

    # print number of faces detected in the image
    print('Number of faces detected:', len(faces))

    # get bounding box for each detected face
    for (x,y,w,h) in faces:
        # add bounding box to color image
        cv2.rectangle(img,(x,y),(x+w,y+h),(255,255,0),2)

    # convert BGR image to RGB for plotting
    cv_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

    # display the image, along with bounding box
    plt.imshow(cv_rgb)
    plt.show()

show_face(human_files[0])

Number of faces detected: 1

Before using any of the face detectors, it is standard procedure to convert the images to grayscale. The detectMultiScale function executes the classifier stored in face_cascade and takes the grayscale image as a parameter.

In the above code, faces is a numpy array of detected faces, where each row corresponds to a detected face. Each detected face is a 1D array with four entries that specifies the bounding box of the detected face. The first two entries in the array (extracted in the above code as x and y) specify the horizontal and vertical positions of the top left corner of the bounding box. The last two entries in the array (extracted here as w and h) specify the width and height of the box.

Write a Human Face Detector¶

We can use this procedure to write a function that returns True if a human face is detected in an image and False otherwise. This function, aptly named face_detector, takes a string-valued file path to an image as input and appears in the code block below.

In [3]:
# returns "True" if face is detected in image stored at img_path
def face_detector(img_path):
    face_cascade = cv2.CascadeClassifier('haarcascades/haarcascade_frontalface_alt.xml')
    img = cv2.imread(img_path)
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray)
    return len(faces) > 0

Obtain Pre-trained VGG-16 Model¶

The code cell below downloads the VGG-16 model, along with weights that have been trained on ImageNet, a very large, very popular dataset used for image classification and other vision tasks. ImageNet contains over 10 million URLs, each linking to an image containing an object from one of 1000 categories.

In [14]:

Given an image, this pre-trained VGG-16 model returns a prediction (derived from the 1000 possible categories in ImageNet) for the object that is contained in the image.

(IMPLEMENTATION) Making Predictions with a Pre-trained Model¶

In the next code cell, you will write a function that accepts a path to an image (such as 'dogImages/train/001.Affenpinscher/Affenpinscher_00001.jpg') as input and returns the index corresponding to the ImageNet class that is predicted by the pre-trained VGG-16 model. The output should always be an integer between 0 and 999, inclusive.

Before writing the function, make sure that you take the time to learn how to appropriately pre-process tensors for pre-trained models in the PyTorch documentation.

In [18]:
from PIL import Image
import torchvision.transforms as transforms

def VGG16_predict(img_path):
    '''
    Use pre-trained VGG-16 model to obtain index corresponding to 
    predicted ImageNet class for image at specified path
    
    Args:
        img_path: path to an image
        
    Returns:
        Index corresponding to VGG-16 model's prediction
    '''
    data_transform = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize(224),
                                         transforms.CenterCrop(224),
                                         transforms.ToTensor(),
                                         transforms.Normalize((0.5, 0.5, 0.5), (0.5, 0.5, 0.5))
                                        ])
    
    img = Image.open(img_path)
    data = data_transform(img).unsqueeze(0)
    
    if torch.cuda.is_available():
        data = data.cuda()

    VGG16.eval()
    _, output = torch.max(VGG16(data), 1)
    
    return output.item() # predicted class index

(IMPLEMENTATION) Write a Dog Detector¶

While looking at the dictionary, you will notice that the categories corresponding to dogs appear in an uninterrupted sequence and correspond to dictionary keys 151-268, inclusive, to include all categories from 'Chihuahua' to 'Mexican hairless'. Thus, in order to check to see if an image is predicted to contain a dog by the pre-trained VGG-16 model, we need only check if the pre-trained model predicts an index between 151 and 268 (inclusive).

Use these ideas to complete the dog_detector function below, which returns True if a dog is detected in an image (and False if not).

In [19]:
def dog_detector(img_path):
    if 151 <= VGG16_predict(img_path) <= 268:
        return True
    else:
        return False

# Create generic helper function
def custom_dog_detector(img_path, model, input_size):
    data_transform = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize(input_size),
                                         transforms.CenterCrop(input_size),
                                         transforms.ToTensor(),
                                         transforms.Normalize((0.5, 0.5, 0.5), (0.5, 0.5, 0.5))
                                        ])
    img = Image.open(img_path)
    data = data_transform(img).unsqueeze(0)
    data = data.cuda() if torch.cuda.is_available() else data.cpu()

    model.eval()
    _, output = torch.max(model(data), 1)
    
    if 151 <= output.item() <= 268:
        return True
    else:
        return False

Step 3: Create a CNN to Classify Dog Breeds (from Scratch)¶

Now that we have functions for detecting humans and dogs in images, we need a way to predict breed from images. In this step, you will create a CNN that classifies dog breeds. You must create your CNN from scratch (so, you can't use transfer learning yet!), and you must attain a test accuracy of at least 10%. In Step 4 of this notebook, you will have the opportunity to use transfer learning to create a CNN that attains greatly improved accuracy.

We mention that the task of assigning breed to dogs from images is considered exceptionally challenging. To see why, consider that even a human would have trouble distinguishing between a Brittany and a Welsh Springer Spaniel.

Brittany Welsh Springer Spaniel

It is not difficult to find other dog breed pairs with minimal inter-class variation (for instance, Curly-Coated Retrievers and American Water Spaniels).

Curly-Coated Retriever American Water Spaniel

Likewise, recall that labradors come in yellow, chocolate, and black. Your vision-based algorithm will have to conquer this high intra-class variation to determine how to classify all of these different shades as the same breed.

Yellow Labrador Chocolate Labrador Black Labrador

We also mention that random chance presents an exceptionally low bar: setting aside the fact that the classes are slightly imabalanced, a random guess will provide a correct answer roughly 1 in 133 times, which corresponds to an accuracy of less than 1%.

Remember that the practice is far ahead of the theory in deep learning. Experiment with many different architectures, and trust your intuition. And, of course, have fun!

    transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),

    transforms.ToTensor(),

])

Question 3: Describe your chosen procedure for preprocessing the data.

  • How does your code resize the images (by cropping, stretching, etc)? What size did you pick for the input tensor, and why?
  • Did you decide to augment the dataset? If so, how (through translations, flips, rotations, etc)? If not, why not?

Answer:

  • Resize method: I used RandomResizedCrop to both resize and then crop to the necessaryd dimensions, since all the photos might be coming in different sizes and formats (e.g. portrait or landscape)
  • Input tensor size: I chose to go with 224, which is the standard image sizes for some of the ImageNet competition images. This would also help to narrow the focus of the NN on the dogs, which I presume are the subject of the image/at the forefront.
    • However, in transfer learning later on I reshape it to 299 to complement the Inception V3 model.
    • At the bottom of this network I run a small experiment with the CV image detector to examine why it detected a human face in the image of a cat.
  • Augmentation: Since dogs are active creatures (hehe) photos of them might come in all angles and directions e.g. a dog lying down.... Thus, I did some simple HorizontalFlip and Rotation transforms.
    • I only applied the augmentation to the training set to maintain fairness when evaluating the validation & test sets across different models.

(IMPLEMENTATION) Model Architecture¶

Create a CNN to classify dog breed. Use the template in the code cell below.

In [31]:
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F

# define the CNN architecture
class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        
        # go deeper is better
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=32, out_channels=64, kernel_size=5, stride=1, padding=2)
        self.conv2_bn = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)   #batchnorm to speed up traiing
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1)
        self.conv3_bn = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(5184, 1032)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(1032, 516)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(516, 133)
        
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)
        self.maxpool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(3, 3)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.4) # higher is better
    
    def forward(self, x):
        
        x = F.elu(self.conv1(x))
        x = self.maxpool(x)
        
        x = F.elu(self.conv2_bn(self.conv2(x)))
        x = self.maxpool(x)  
        
        x = F.elu(self.conv3_bn(self.conv3(x)))
        x = self.maxpool2(x)
        
        # flatten
        x = x.view(x.shape[0], -1)
        
        x = F.elu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        
        x = F.elu(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        
        x = self.fc3(x)

        return x

Question 4: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step.

Answer:

First Submission

  • Convolutional layers: First I tried out_channels=32 in the first CNN layer, but even after training for ~80 epochs the validation loss was still quite high. Thus, I switched to out_channels=64 in the first layer. I was also motivated by the previous MNIST autoencoder exercise (where we introduced noise), and figured if I used 64 channels there, in a grayscale image, all the more I should be looking at more channels in a RGB image
    • I also experimented with using a larger kernel and stride in the second conv layer since there many out_channels in the previous layer
    • I continued to use maxpooling on all layers to help reduce dimension sizes too
  • Fully connected layers: Since there were a lot of nodes coming out of the CNN layers, I went with 3 FC layers to gradually bring the dimensions down. I chose to use log_softmax in conjunction with an NLLLoss criteria.
    • I used dropout on the first 2 layers to prevent overffiting
  • Learning rate: Initially, I set the lr=0.01 but I felt that training was going very slowly. Thus, I increased it to lr=0.05
  • Epochs: I set n_epochs = 100. However I'm not sure when the model stopped training as the output stopped printing/GPU shut itself down after awhile. I estimate it ended around 60-80 epochs.
self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=32, kernel_size=5, stride=1, padding=2)
self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=32, out_channels=4, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
self.fc1 = nn.Linear(4 * 28 * 28, 1032)
self.fc2 = nn.Linear(1032, 516)
self.fc3 = nn.Linear(516, 133)
self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)
self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)
---
x = F.relu(self.conv1(x))
x = self.maxpool(x)
x = F.relu(self.conv2(x))
x = self.maxpool(x)  
x = F.relu(self.conv3(x))
x = self.maxpool(x)
x = x.view(x.shape[0], -1)
x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
x = self.dropout(x)
x = F.relu(self.fc2(x))
x = self.dropout(x)
x = F.log_softmax(self.fc3(x), dim=1)

Second Submission

  • Based on the feedback I received in the first submission, I also tested out a new architecture.
  • I made the convolutional layers get deeper further into the model, as traditionally observed
    • Towards the third layer I increased the kernel and stride, as well as max pooling, to reduce the number of nodes after flattening
  • I used BatchNorm to speed up training since the previous algorithm would take a long time
  • I used a higher Dropout value at 0.4 instead of 0.2
  • I experimented with the ELU activation function instead of ReLU.
  • I stopped the model after 30 epochs. Here, the validation loss was already ~3.9, which is much faster than my previous model.

(IMPLEMENTATION) Train and Validate the Model¶

Train and validate your model in the code cell below. Save the final model parameters at filepath 'model_scratch.pt'.

In [36]:
from utils import active_session
In [37]:
def train(n_epochs, loaders, model, optimizer, criterion, use_cuda, save_path):
    """returns trained model"""
    # initialize tracker for minimum validation loss
    valid_loss_min = np.Inf 
    
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        # initialize variables to monitor training and validation loss
        train_loss = 0.0
        valid_loss = 0.0
        
        ###################
        # train the model #
        ###################
        model.train()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['train']):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            ## find the loss and update the model parameters accordingly
            ## record the average training loss, using something like
            ## train_loss = train_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - train_loss))
            output = model(data)
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            train_loss = train_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - train_loss))
            
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            
        ######################    
        # validate the model #
        ######################
        model.eval()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['valid']):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            ## update the average validation loss
            output = model(data)
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            valid_loss = valid_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - valid_loss))
            
        # print training/validation statistics 
        print('Epoch: {} \tTraining Loss: {:.6f} \tValidation Loss: {:.6f}'.format(
            epoch, 
            train_loss,
            valid_loss
            ))
        
        ## TODO: save the model if validation loss has decreased
        if valid_loss < valid_loss_min:
            print('..Validation loss decreased ({:.6f} --> {:.6f}).  Saving model ...'.format(
                valid_loss_min, valid_loss))
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
            valid_loss_min = valid_loss
            
    # return trained model
    return model

(IMPLEMENTATION) Test the Model¶

Try out your model on the test dataset of dog images. Use the code cell below to calculate and print the test loss and accuracy. Ensure that your test accuracy is greater than 10%.

In [39]:
def test(loaders, model, criterion, use_cuda):

    # monitor test loss and accuracy
    test_loss = 0.
    correct = 0.
    total = 0.

    model.eval()
    for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['test']):
        # move to GPU
        if use_cuda:
            data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
        # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
        output = model(data)
        # calculate the loss
        loss = criterion(output, target)
        # update average test loss 
        test_loss = test_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - test_loss))
        # convert output probabilities to predicted class
        pred = output.data.max(1, keepdim=True)[1]
        # compare predictions to true label
        correct += np.sum(np.squeeze(pred.eq(target.data.view_as(pred))).cpu().numpy())
        total += data.size(0)
            
    print('Test Loss: {:.6f}\n'.format(test_loss))

    print('\nTest Accuracy: %2d%% (%2d/%2d)' % (
        100. * correct / total, correct, total))

    transforms.RandomResizedCrop(INCEPTION_INPUT_SIZE),
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.3),
    transforms.RandomRotation(30),

Question 5: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step. Describe why you think the architecture is suitable for the current problem.

Answer:

Architecture

  1. Among the pretrained models (VGG16, ResNet, and Inception), I chose Inception as it has one of the better performances with reasonable training time. Resnet-152 has the best performance, but has 10x the number of parameters to optimize for.
    • See table of comparison at bottom of this article: https://towardsdatascience.com/the-w3h-of-alexnet-vggnet-resnet-and-inception-7baaaecccc96
  2. After downloading the Inception model, I changed the number of output nodes to the number of classes, 133. I did not add any extra layers
  3. I choose to retrain all the weights of the initial model.
    • (Partly because everytime I tried to freeze the weights of all the other layers and only leave the FC layer, pytorch threw an error saying there were no gradients to optimize)

Training

  • Loss function is CrossEntropyLoss, since this is a classification task, and I chose to set a lr=0.05 based on my experience with the scratch model.
  • The first 1-2 training epochs already gave me a much more promising validation score model_scratch (~1.2 Training Loss -- print statements below don't reflect it as I added epochs later on)
  • After 4 epochs, the model was at ~0.98 training loss and performed >60% on the test set.
  • In total, I trained for 15 epochs for a final train loss of 0.66 and validation loss of 0.53, and test accuracy of 74%. From the training output we can see that the model is slowly converging and not overfitting yet, but I chose to stop training here.

(IMPLEMENTATION) Predict Dog Breed with the Model¶

Write a function that takes an image path as input and returns the dog breed (Affenpinscher, Afghan hound, etc) that is predicted by your model.

In [51]:
from PIL import Image

model_transfer.load_state_dict(torch.load('model_transfer/model_transfer_3.pt'))

# list of class names by index, i.e. a name can be accessed like class_names[0]
class_names = [item[4:].replace("_", " ") for item in train_data.classes]

def predict_breed_transfer(img_path, model, top_k = 1):
    data_transform = transforms.Compose([transforms.RandomResizedCrop(299),
                                         transforms.ToTensor()])
    img = Image.open(img_path)
    data = data_transform(img).unsqueeze(0)
    
    if torch.cuda.is_available():
        data = data.cuda()
        model = model.cuda()
    else:
        data = data.cpu()
        model = model.cpu()
        
    model.eval()
    output = model(data)
    
    # Take top k outputs
    probs, preds = torch.topk(output.data, k=top_k, dim=1)
    if torch.cuda.is_available():
        probs = probs.cpu().numpy()[0]
        preds = preds.cpu().numpy()[0]
    else:
        probs, preds = probs.numpy()[0], preds.numpy()[0]
    breeds = [class_names[p] for p in preds]
    
    return list(probs), breeds

Step 5: Write your Algorithm¶

Write an algorithm that accepts a file path to an image and first determines whether the image contains a human, dog, or neither. Then,

  • if a dog is detected in the image, return the predicted breed.
  • if a human is detected in the image, return the resembling dog breed.
  • if neither is detected in the image, provide output that indicates an error.

You are welcome to write your own functions for detecting humans and dogs in images, but feel free to use the face_detector and human_detector functions developed above. You are required to use your CNN from Step 4 to predict dog breed.

Some sample output for our algorithm is provided below, but feel free to design your own user experience!

(IMPLEMENTATION) Write your Algorithm¶

In [78]:
def run_app(img_path, detector_model, breed_model, input_size = 299):
    ## handle cases for a human face, dog, and neither
    is_dog = custom_dog_detector(img_path, detector_model, input_size)
    is_human = face_detector(img_path)
    probs, breeds = predict_breed_transfer(img_path, breed_model, top_k = 2)
    
    plt.figure()
    if is_dog:
        title = "woof woof woof (hello in dogspeak)!!\n"
        if probs[0] > 60:
            title += "you must be a cousin of my friend " + breeds[0] + "\n"
        else:
            title += "i'm a little unsure, but i'd say\n"
            title += str(round(probs[0], 1)) + "% " + breeds[0] + '\n'
            title += str(round(probs[1], 1)) + "% " + breeds[1]
    elif is_human:
        title = "darn humans trying to trick the system...\ni'll read ur face anyway....\n"
        if probs[0] > 60:
            title += "you look like a " + breeds[0] + "\n"
        else:
            title += "i'm a little unsure, but i'd say\n"
            title += str(round(probs[0], 1)) + "% " + breeds[0] + '\n'
            title += str(round(probs[1], 1)) + "% " + breeds[1]
    else:
        title = "ERROR - neither human nor dog... are u a cat?!"
    
    plt.imshow(Image.open(img_path))
    plt.title(title)

Step 6: Test Your Algorithm¶

In this section, you will take your new algorithm for a spin! What kind of dog does the algorithm think that you look like? If you have a dog, does it predict your dog's breed accurately? If you have a cat, does it mistakenly think that your cat is a dog?

(IMPLEMENTATION) Test Your Algorithm on Sample Images!¶

Test your algorithm at least six images on your computer. Feel free to use any images you like. Use at least two human and two dog images.

Question 6: Is the output better than you expected :) ? Or worse :( ? Provide at least three possible points of improvement for your algorithm.

Answer¶

Evaluation

  • The model finds it difficult to differentiate between slight variations in breeds (e.g. bull mastiff and mastiff)
  • Interestingly, the model generates pretty low probabilities for all dog breeds when we input a human (for benchmark, 1/133 = 0.75%).
    • The percentage for a cat (~4% for the top breed) is slightly higher, but still lower than for dog examples (~10%)
  • Dog detector has mixed performance on less-than-traditional images
    • Dug from up (cartoon dog): OK
    • Dog with stretched nose: OK
    • Dog with glasses: not ok
    • Just dog ear/nose features: not ok
    • Kendall jenner with dog filter: not ok

Areas of improvement

  • Add more training data for the different classes so the model can learn more!
    • Could also add more "interesting" training data points like a dog with glasses on it (see additional examples below)
  • Since the validation loss was still decreasing, there might be space to train the model for several more epochs for higher accuracy
    • Although it's classifying right, the difference between the prob for the first & second breeds is pretty small, so we can aim for greater distinction between classes
  • It might be possible to provide greater distinction by first classifying dogs by higher level families / breeds, and then trying to differentiate between species within that family. That would help reduce the number of output classes and build better distinction between the predicted probabilities.

In the process, I realized that it was detecting a very small area near the cat's ear as a face, possibly because the input image was large (>1000px) and provided enough fidelity. Instead, when I resized the image, the human face disappeared.
